-- Crude Options Volatility at Seven-Day High as Futures Decline
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-07-22T20:00:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-22/crude-options-volatility-at-seven-day-high-as-futures-decline.html
Crude options volatility rose to the
highest level since July 11 as the underlying futures fell for
the first time in four days.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options value, was 22.2 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  as of 3:35 p.m., up from 21.47 on July 19.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery slid
93 cents to settle at $106.94 a barrel on the Nymex. The front-month August contract, which expired today, declined $1.14 to
$106.91.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
September $90 puts, which fell 5 cents to 6 cents a barrel on
volume of 23,279 lots traded as of 3:38 p.m. September $95 puts
were the second-most active, declining 5 cents to 17 cents on
volume of 8,280 contracts.  Puts accounted for 71 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, calls made up 57 percent of 160,289
contracts exchanged.  September $110 calls were the most-active options on July
19, with 8,374 contracts changing hands as they rose 16 cents to
$1.58 a barrel. September $100 puts increased 1 cent to 52 cents
on 7,240 lots.  Open interest was highest for September $90 puts, with
40,913 contracts. Next were December $80 puts with 38,602 lots
and December $90 puts with 37,281.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporters on this story:
